http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Theatre Curriculum Standards for 5th Grade.
Script Writing - Students will write scripts through improvising, drafting, and refining scripts based on personal experience and heritage, imagination, literature, and history.
Examine the principles of scene writing.
Participate in script writing by structuring the development and resolution of dramatic problems.
Explore personal situations through the creation of scripted scenes.
Illustrate meaning and character through dialogue.
Character Acting - Students will develop basic acting skills by portraying characters in improvised and scripted scenes.
Apply sensory and emotional experiences to create a character.
Use imagination to form and to express thought, feeling and character.
Use characterization to solve dramatic problems in individual and group settings.
Utilize improvisational skills and techniques in creating a character.
Employ movement to express thought, feeling and characterization.
Employ vocal techniques to express thought, feeling and characterization.
Scene Design - Students will design by developing environments for improvised and scripted scenes.
Employ the functions of various technical elements such as visual elements and aural qualities.
Determine design elements needed for improvised or scripted scenes.
Experiment with creating costumes, properties and scenery for improvised or scripted scenes.
Utilize safety procedures when creating design elements.
Directing - Students will direct by organizing rehearsals for improvised and scripted scenes.
Demonstrate an understanding of the responsibilities of the director.
Develop leadership and collaborative skills through directing improvised and scripted scenes.
Research - Students will research by using cultural and historical information to support improvised and scripted scenes.
Explore the contributions of people in a multicultural society for use in improvised and scripted scenes.
Examine improvised or scripted scenes through the appropriate historical context.

Theatrical Presentation - Students will compare and incorporate art forms by analyzing methods of presentation and audience response for theatre, dramatic media (such as film, television, and electronic media), and other art forms.
Explore other art forms as they contrast and/or relate to theatre.
Examine dramatic media as a forum for the synthesis of all of the arts.
Integrate other art forms into the creation of dramatic projects.
Understand the role of the audience and demonstrate appropriate audience etiquette.
Scene Comprehension - Students will analyze, evaluate and construct meanings from improvised and scripted scenes and from theatre, film, television, and electronic media productions.
Respond to a variety of theatrical experiences.
Analyze creative drama and formal theatre, film and multimedia productions.
Context - Students will understand context by analyzing the role of theatre, film, television and electronic media in the community and in other cultures.
Explain how elements of various cultures are reflected in theatre, film, television and electronic media.
Understand the influence of theatre, film, television and electronic media on society throughout history.
